			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				From what they have told me, Verant uses high encryption to protect the userID and password while in transit from the client computer (you) to the server (them).  If this is indeed the case, packet sniffers can't be used to steal your password while in transit, but rather your own computer must be compromised: either you've told your friend your userID/password, there's a key logger on your comp, or someone just plain guessed it.<BR>
<BR>
Of course, it's just as possible that Verant lies about the encryption; I'm too lazy to start analyzing the packets and check if the stuff is sent out in plain text, or if there's something that smells like decent cryptography.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
