				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				I have been thinking about this more and more.  I believe your reasons for this are as follows.<BR>
<BR>
EBAY and the like sites:<BR>
P1 Sells account.<BR>
P2 Buys account changes CC info and Password.<BR>
P1 calls says my account has been stolen.<BR>
SOE changes password back.<BR>
P2 calls says my account has been stolen.<BR>
SOE ban account!<BR>
<BR>
Unfortuanlty even if someone sniffed my U/P over hte internet steps 3-6 would still happen and SOE has no way of knowing if the account was stolen or sold.  I still am not in favor of the account being banned, thus I offer the following solution.<BR>
<BR>
Don't allow people to update Credit Card and personal info online.  Thus if someone tries to change the credit card and the names don't match, don't let it happen or make it have to be a customer service call, verifying origional info and new info.  Keep a record of it.  Thus if I have never changed the billing info or the name on my account and it gets hacked, I WANT MY CHARACTER'S STUFF BACK.<BR>
<BR>
I have also seen the following suggested on the news group.  If the person that has had their account hacked wants thier stuff back, offer a per hour rate to have a CS person look into the situation, saying this is above and beyond the normal CS service duties.  People who really care will pay, and people that are trying to scam I don't think will.<BR>
<BR>
I would be very interested to open this idea up to more debate or at least tell us customers what reasons you have to not implement this idea.<BR>
<BR>
Jason Burgoyne, owner of 2 accounts and very concerned<BR>

